  "title": "Writ substrate & the quest/topic writ type",
  "body": "_Imported from `.scratch/conversation-topics-as-writs.md` (2026-04-10)._\n\n## Opened With\n\nCoco's startup routine eagerly reads `.scratch/recent-sessions/*.md`. It's expensive, incomplete under concurrent sessions, and uses history where current state is what's needed. We need continuing-context capture that's durable, queryable, and visible to autonomous planning agents — not trapped in Coco's scratch files.\n\nThe proposal: treat a **writ** as a durable, typed, tree-structured entity in Stacks, where the **type** carries the semantic meaning. `mandate` is obligation; `brief` is spec-in-progress; a new type — call it `topic` for now — is an area of inquiry. Adding the type gets us tree structure, lifecycle states, typed links, CDC events, queryability, a UI surface, and a CLI surface *for free*.\n\nThe key technical unlock: Spider only dispatches writ types explicitly mapped to a rig template. A writ type with no mapping is **inert** — it uses the writ substrate for storage and visibility but nothing tries to execute it. No special-case branches needed; the mapping table already enforces it.\n\nv1 scope is deliberately narrow: declare the type, establish a body template (Opened With / Summary / Notes), update Coco's workflow to use it, migrate prior scratch content. Sidecar books, structured decision capture, and ratification flows are v2.\n\n## Summary\n\nShipped as the `quest` writ type, documented in `.claude/skills/quests/SKILL.md`. Coco's startup and wrap-up routines query quests instead of reading session files. The Opened With / Summary / Notes body convention is in active use. This quest is itself the import of the original design doc.\n\n**Resolved on the way in:**\n\n- Clerk body-edit gap — `nsg writ edit` handles non-draft quest bodies, which is what the workflow depends on.\n- Writ vocabulary documentation debt — metaphor and supporting docs now frame writ as typed substrate rather than obligation-flavored.\n\n**Still open** (tracked as child quests):\n\n- Plugin-contributed writ types — currently on the `guild.json` escape hatch; the `contributes` manifest pattern remains undesigned.\n- Concurrent session writes to the same quest body — last-write-wins risk, unmitigated.\n- Decisions & ratification (the deferred v2) — decisions live in prose today, not as queryable records.\n- Naming — \"quest\" doesn't quite sit right; exploring alternatives.\n\n## Notes\n\n- Spider's dispatch-is-opt-in design is the load-bearing insight. Worth remembering any time we want a \"parasitic\" writ type that stores state without triggering execution.\n- Astrolabe's existing `Decision` and `DecisionAnalysis` types, plus Spider's `InputRequestDoc` + `patron-input` block type, are the reference shapes for the v2 decisions work.\n- GSD's threads/seeds/backlog schemas inspired the body-template convention. (Original research cached at `.scratch/gsd-research/` during design; now superseded by the shipped mechanism.)",
